My friend Toby (@mandy3284) weighed in with a nice answer that I didn't really expect:

<iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/115785360?title=0&amp;byline=0&amp;portrait=0&amp;color=8072ff" width="500" height="466" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe> <p><a href="http://vimeo.com/115785360">Adding Parabolas</a> from <a href="http://vimeo.com/sundialtone">Toby Schachman</a> on <a href="https://vimeo.com">Vimeo</a>.</p>

Toby's solution uses a third vantage point for understanding parabolas. It is not based directly on the algebra of polynomials, nor on classical constructive geometry. Instead, it is based on finite differences.

Suppose we have a table of x, y values, and the x values are evenly spaced.

[[table]]

How can we tell if the entries of this table are points that all lie on the same parabola.

From a *finite difference* perspective, a parabola is an ordered set of points with constant 2nd differences.

Given part of a table like this, we can *extrapolate* further values by first filling in the (constant) 2nd differences, then filling in the first differences implied by earlier values and the 2nd differences, and then filling in values implied by earlier values and first differences.

We can also *interpolate* intermediate values by demanding constant second differences, and consistency with known values

1       y_2 - 1      9 - 2y_2 + 1
y_2     9 - y_2      y_4 - 18 + y_2
9       y_4 - 9      25 - 2y_4 + 9
y_4     25 - y_4
25

[[system of 3 equations in 3 unknowns]]

As Toby explains in the video, when we add two functions, the first and second differences also add, and the sum of two constant functions is also a constant function.

